{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14287"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14287"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.11,0.53,0.01,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112367"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6982"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94415"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"403"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45913"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112367"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of right flank pain, fever, and dysuria. She was diagnosed with acute pyelonephritis by her general practitioner three days ago and started on oral amoxicillin and clavulanate. Despite taking the antibiotics as prescribed, her symptoms have worsened. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and takes metformin. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 102/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 21/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has right costovertebral angle tenderness. Abdominal examination reveals right flank tenderness but no guarding or rebound tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine microscopy (from three days ago): leucocytes \u0026gt;100 cells/\u03bcL (\u0026lt;10), erythrocytes 20 cells/\u03bcL (\u0026lt;10), epithelial cells 5 cells/\u03bcL (\u0026lt;10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine culture and sensitivity (from three days ago): \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E sensitive to amoxicillin/clavulanate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 18 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 180 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence intravenous amoxicillin/clavulanate","Arrange urgent urology consultation","Perform CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis","Commence metaraminol infusion","Repeat urine microscopy, culture, and sensitivity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a complicated urinary tract infection (UTI) that has not responded to initial antibiotic therapy. The urine culture from three days ago confirms \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E sensitive to the prescribed amoxicillin/clavulanate, yet her symptoms have worsened despite appropriate antibiotic coverage. Given her persistent symptoms, worsening clinical condition, and the presence of risk factors (diabetes), there is a high suspicion for a more serious condition, such as a renal abscess or pyelonephritis with obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Imaging (CT or ultrasound) should be considered if the patient remains febrile after 72 hours of appropriate antibiotic treatment to exclude urinary obstruction or renal abscess. The fact that the patient is on appropriate antibiotics based on culture sensitivities but is not improving strongly suggests a complication requiring source control. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence intravenous amoxicillin/clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would simply be changing the route of administration of the same antibiotic. While intravenous antibiotics may achieve higher tissue concentrations, the failure to respond to oral therapy despite organism sensitivity suggests a complication that requires investigation rather than just a change in antibiotic route.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange urgent urology consultation\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary, but it would be more appropriate after obtaining imaging results to guide the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence metaraminol infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate at this stage. While the patient\u0027s blood pressure is on the lower side, fluid resuscitation would be a more appropriate initial step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat urine microscopy, culture, and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to provide additional useful information at this stage. The patient already has a recent culture showing a sensitive organism, and repeating the test would delay the diagnosis of potential complications. The failure to respond to appropriate antibiotics suggests a structural complication rather than a different organism or resistance pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of persistent or worsening UTI symptoms despite appropriate antibiotic therapy, especially in patients with risk factors like diabetes, clinicians should have a low threshold for further investigation with imaging studies. This approach helps identify complications such as renal abscesses, which require source control as mainstay of management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Persistent fever after 72 hours of appropriate antibiotic therapy should prompt investigation for complications such as abscess formation or obstruction.","Renal abscesses often fail to respond to standard antibiotic therapy and require source control to address the root of the problem."],"references":["Okafor C, Onyeaso E. Perinephric Abscess. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536936/","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Acute pyelonephritis in adults. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (Australia): Therapeutic Guidelines; Published Mar 2025 [cited 2025 Aug 30]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14287"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T20:49:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T20:50:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6982"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112367"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}